snippet.textDisplay: Honestly this design has a feel of fresh air. I think Motorola took a gamble, and they landed on the motherload. This is what a cellphone is supposed to be, small, portable, convenient. The only things that worry me are battery-life (for which i would tolerate a tad larger size), the life expectancy of the screen as well as fragility of both the screen and the wear of the mechanism since it is a new design.  But you cant have a new concept without risks and doubts. I am honestly interested to see where this takes the cellphone market. Competition breeds progress, i hope this gives us some great products.  A big bravo to Motorola.
snippet.textOriginal: Honestly this design has a feel of fresh air. I think Motorola took a gamble, and they landed on the motherload. This is what a cellphone is supposed to be, small, portable, convenient. The only things that worry me are battery-life (for which i would tolerate a tad larger size), the life expectancy of the screen as well as fragility of both the screen and the wear of the mechanism since it is a new design. Competition breeds progress, i hope this gives us some great products.  A big bravo to Motorola.

snippet.textDisplay: Looks cool and all, but is a folding your phone really necessary and something the public want with the current limitations of said technology? So much screen real-estate around the edges and top disappears, not to mention the massive chunky area at the bottom(?), is needed to accommodate what is essentially an age old feature. Phones are now pretty thin, so instead of a long slim phone you'll now be pocketing a stubby short brick. Its not like you're going to put your keys etc in the same pocket as your device (to avoid scratching) so what problem was really solved here? Also, the battery is now restricted to half the phones interior which I can only assume will significantly affect battery life? And now you also have a device that's on hinges and has a screen that moves whenever you fold it, and as we all know: more movable parts means a higher the chance of something breaking. It seems as this phone was designed to appeal to people's nostalgia, not efficiently compete with other products.
